### Implicit Differentiation

So far, we have dealt with functions that are mostly explicit (e.g. \(y=x^{3}+3\) and \(y=\tan x\) ). However, the dependent variable \(y\) may not always be expressed in terms of the independent variable \(x\) explicitly (e.g. \(5xy^{2}-x^{3}y+3=0\) ).

In such cases, we will use the **chain rule** to find \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\). Such a process is known as **implicit differentiation**.

#### Example 1.3.1

Differentiate the following with respect to \(x\).

(i) \(y\), (ii) \(y^{2}\), (iii) \(xy\), (iv) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\), (v) \(\left(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\right)^{2}\).

_Solution:_

(i) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\big{(}y\big{)}=\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\). (ii) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\big{(}y^{2}\big{)}=\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d }y}\big{(}y^{2}\big{)}\cdot\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=2y\dfrac{\mathrm{d }y}{\mathrm{d}x}\). (iii) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\big{(}xy\big{)}=x\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d }x}+y\). (iv) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\bigg{(}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\bigg{)} =\dfrac{\mathrm{d}^{2}y}{\mathrm{d}x^{2}}\). (v) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\bigg{[}\bigg{(}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} \bigg{)}^{2}\bigg{]}=2\bigg{(}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\bigg{)}\dfrac{ \mathrm{d}^{2}y}{\mathrm{d}x^{2}}\).

In general,

(a) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\big{(}y^{n}\big{)}=\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{ d}y}\big{(}y^{n}\big{)}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=ny^{n-1}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{ \mathrm{d}x}\), where \(n\) is a rational number. (b) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\big{(}\mathrm{f}\big{(}y\big{)}\big{)}= \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}y}\big{(}\mathrm{f}\big{(}y\big{)}\big{)}\dfrac{ \mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=\mathrm{f}^{\prime}(y)\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d }x}\).

**Example 1.3.2**:

Find \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\) in terms of \(x\) and \(y\) if (a) \(x^{2}+y^{3}=xy\), (b) \(3x^{2}-7y^{2}+4xy-8x=0\),

(c) \(\cos^{-1}y=x+y\), (d) \(y=\tan^{-1}(y-x)\).

_Solution:_

(a) \(x^{2}+y^{3}=xy\).

Differentiate implicitly w.r.t. \(x\), we get

\[2x+3y^{2}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =x\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}+y\] \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =\dfrac{2x-y}{x-3y^{2}}\,.\]

(b) \(3x^{2}-7y^{2}+4xy-8x=0\).

Differentiate implicitly w.r.t. \(x\), we get

\[6x-14y\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}+\left(4x\dfrac{\mathrm{d} y}{\mathrm{d}x}+4y\right)-8=0\] \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =\dfrac{6x+4y-8}{14y-4x}=\dfrac{3x+2y-4}{7y-2x}\,.\]

(c) \(\cos^{-1}y=x+y\).

Differentiate implicitly w.r.t. \(x\), we get

\[-\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}\cdot\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =1+\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} \cos^{-1}y=x+y\] \[\Rightarrow y=\cos(x+y)\,.\]

Differentiate implicitly w.r.t. \(x\), we get

\[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =-\dfrac{1}{1+\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}}\] \[=-\dfrac{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}}{\sqrt{1-y^{2}}+1}\,.\]

(d) \(y=\tan^{-1}\left(y-x\right)\Rightarrow\tan y=y-x\).

Differentiate implicitly w.r.t. \(x\),

\[\left(\sec^{2}y\right)\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}-1\] \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\sec^{2}y-1\right) =-1\] \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\tan^{2}y\right) =-1\] \[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x} =-\cot^{2}y.\]

**Example 1.3.3**:

Find \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\) in terms of \(x\) and \(y\) if (a) \(y=x^{*},\ x>0\), (b) \(y=\left(\ln x\right)^{*}.\)

_Solution:_

(a) \(y=x^{*}\) (b) Taking "\(\ln\)" on both sides, we get \(\ln y=x\ln x\) Differentiate implicitly with respect to \(x\), we get

\(\dfrac{1}{y}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=x\left(\dfrac{1}{x}\right)+(1)\ln x\)

\(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=y\left(1+\ln x\right)=x^{*}\left(1+\ln x\right)\).
**Note:**: If the expression to be differentiated is defined explicitly, the derivative should be in **explicit form** as well.
**Note:**: The process of taking "\(\ln\)" on both sides before carrying out implicit differentiation is called **logarithmic differentiation.**: In general, logarithmic differentiation is useful for expressions of the form \(u^{*}\), where both \(u\) and \(v\) are **non-constant** expressions of \(x\) and/or \(y\).

### Parametric Differentiation

We have seen curves defined by a pair of parametric equations. We shall look at how to evaluate the gradient function in such cases.

Given a set of parametric equations: \(\begin{cases}x=\mathrm{f}(t)\\ y=\mathrm{g}(t)\end{cases}\), we may evaluate \(\begin{cases}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}=\mathrm{f}^{\prime}(t)\\ \dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t}=\mathrm{g}^{\prime}(t).\end{cases}\)

The gradient function can be found as: \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} \cdot\dfrac{\mathrm{d}t}{\mathrm{d}x}=\dfrac{\left[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{ d}t}\right]}{\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}}=\dfrac{\mathrm{g}^{\prime}(t)}{ \mathrm{f}^{\prime}(t)}\). Note: \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}=\dfrac{1}{\dfrac{\mathrm{d}t}{\mathrm{d}x}}\)

Note that the gradient function will also generally be in terms of the parameter \(t\).

### Example 1.4.1

Find the gradient function for the following curves defined parametrically.

(a) \(x=t^{3}\), \(y=t^{2}-t\), (b) \(x=\sqrt[]{t}\), \(y=\cos t\), (c) \(x=t^{2}\), \(y=t+\dfrac{1}{t}\).

_Solution:_

(a) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t}=2t-1\), \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}=3t^{2}\) (b) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}=\dfrac{1}{2}t^{\frac{1}{2}}=\dfrac{1}{2 \sqrt{t}}\), \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t}=-\sin t\)

(c) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t}=1-\dfrac{1}{t^{2}}\), \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}=2t\)

(d) \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=\dfrac{\left[\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} \right]}{\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}}=\dfrac{1-\frac{1}{t^{2}}}{2t}= \dfrac{t^{2}-1}{2t^{3}}\).

**Example 1.4.2**

It is given that \(x=\sec\theta+\tan\theta\) and \(y=\cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta\). Show that

\[x+\frac{1}{x}=2\sec\theta\text{ and }y+\frac{1}{y}=2\text{cosec}\theta.\]

Hence show that \(\frac{\text{d}y}{\text{d}x}=-\frac{1+y^{2}}{1+x^{2}}\).

_Solution:_

\[x+\frac{1}{x} =\sec\theta+\tan\theta+\frac{1}{\sec\theta+\tan\theta}\] \[=\frac{\left(\sec\theta+\tan\theta\right)^{2}+1}{\sec\theta+\tan\theta}\] \[=\frac{\sec^{2}\theta+\tan^{2}\theta+2\sec\theta\tan\theta+1}{ \sec\theta+\tan\theta}\] \[=\frac{2\sec^{2}\theta+2\sec\theta\tan\theta}{\sec\theta+\tan\theta}\] \[=\frac{2\sec\theta\left(\sec\theta+\tan\theta\right)}{\sec\theta +\tan\theta}\] \[=2\sec\theta\text{ (shown).}\]

\[y+\frac{1}{y} =\cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta+\frac{1}{\cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta}\] \[=\frac{\left(\cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta\right)^{2}+1}{\cos\sec \theta+\cot\theta}\] \[=\frac{\cos\sec^{2}\theta+\cot^{2}\theta+2\cos\sec\theta\cot\theta +1}{\cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta}\] \[=\frac{2\cos\sec^{2}\theta+2\cos\sec\theta\cot\theta}{\cos\sec \theta+\cot\theta}\] \[=\frac{2\cos\sec\theta\left(\cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta\right)}{ \cos\sec\theta+\cot\theta}\] \[=2\cos\sec\theta\text{ (shown).}\]

\[\frac{\text{d}y}{\text{d}\theta} =-\text{cosec}\theta\cot\theta-\text{cosec}^{2}\theta=-\text{ cosec}\theta\big{(}\cot\theta+\text{cosec}\theta\big{)}.\] \[\frac{\text{d}x}{\text{d}\theta} =\sec\theta\tan\theta+\sec^{2}\theta=\sec\theta\big{(}\tan\theta+ \sec\theta\big{)}.\]

\[\frac{\text{d}y}{\text{d}x} =\frac{-\text{cosec}\theta\big{(}\cot\theta+\text{cosec}\theta \big{)}}{\sec\theta\big{(}\tan\theta+\sec\theta\big{)}}=\frac{-\frac{1}{2} \Bigg{(}y+\frac{1}{y}\Bigg{)}y}{\frac{1}{2}\Bigg{(}x+\frac{1}{x} \Bigg{)}x}=-\frac{1+y^{2}}{1+x^{2}}\text{ (shown).}\]

### Increasing and Decreasing Functions

A function is said to be strictly increasing (resp. strictly decreasing) when the value of \(\mathsf{f}(x)\) increases (resp. decreases) as the value of \(x\) increases. Mathematically, we have:

**Definition 2.1.1** (Increasing and Decreasing Functions): A function \(\mathsf{f}\) is said to be _strictly increasing_ (resp. _strictly decreasing_) if \(a<b\) implies that \(\mathsf{f}(a)<\mathsf{f}(b)\) (resp. \(\mathsf{f}(a)>\mathsf{f}(b)\)).

Examples: (Strictly increasing functions) \(y=x,\ y=x^{3}+x\). (Strictly decreasing function) \(y=-2x+1\).

For differentiable functions that are neither strictly increasing nor strictly decreasing, we can still determine the interval (say \(I\)) such that the curve is **upward** or **downward sloping** on \(I\). For example, consider the following graph of \(y=\mathsf{f}(x)\).

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|} \hline Range of values & Value of & Gradient of curve & On \(I\), function \\ of \(x\), \(I\) & \(\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)\) or \(\dfrac{\mathsf{d}y}{\mathsf{d}x}\) & \(y=\mathsf{f}(x)\) is & & \(\mathsf{f}\) is... \\ \hline \(x<a\) or \(x>b\) & \(>0\) & positive & upward sloping & strictly increasing \\ \hline \(a<x<b\) & \(<0\) & negative & downward & strictly decreasing \\ \hline \end{tabular}

Hence we can conclude that

(a) If \(\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)>0\) or \(\dfrac{\mathsf{d}y}{\mathsf{d}x}>0\) for all \(x\) in an interval \(I\), then \(\mathsf{f}\) is strictly increasing on \(I\). (b) If \(\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)<0\) or \(\dfrac{\mathsf{d}y}{\mathsf{d}x}<0\) for all \(x\) in an interval \(I\), then \(\mathsf{f}\) is strictly decreasing on \(I\).

### Stationary Points

**Stationary points** are points on the curve where \(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=\mathrm{f}^{\prime}(x)=0\).

There are 3 types of stationary points - local minimum, local maximum and stationary point of inflexion.

From the above diagram, \(A\) is a **local maximum point**.

\(B\) is a **local minimum point**.

\(C_{1}\) and \(C_{2}\) are **stationary points of inflexion**.

\(A\) and \(B\) are called **turning points**, because the sign of the gradient to the curve changes at these points (either from negative to positive or vice versa), and hence the curve "turns" at these points.

In general, we have the following definition:

**Definition 2.2.1**: **(Local maximum and minimum points)**

A point \(\left(k,\mathrm{f}(k)\right)\) lying on the curve \(y=\mathrm{f}(x)\) is said to be a _local maximum_ (resp. _minimum_) _point_ if \(\mathrm{f}(k)\) is greatest (resp. least) value of \(\mathrm{f}(x)\) in an **immediate neighbourhood** of \(k\), i.e. for a small interval of values of \(x\) containing \(k\).

In the above definition, \(\mathrm{f}(k)\) need not be the greatest (least) value of \(\mathrm{f}(x)\) for all \(x\) in \(D_{t}\) and hence the word "_local_". On the other hand, we look at all the values of \(\mathrm{f}(x)\) in \(D_{t}\) to identify the global minimum/maximum point.

_WONDER_

Must the global minimum/maximum be a stationary point?

**Answer:** No.

_WONDER_

Can a graph have no global minimum/maximum point?

**Answer:** Yes. For instance, consider \(\mathrm{f}(x)=2x\), \(0<x<1\).

Note that 0 and 2 does not lie in the range of f.

