### Concavity / Curvature

Recall that

\[\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2}y}{\mathrm{d}x^{2}}=\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\bigg{(} \frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\bigg{)}=\text{rate of change of }\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\text{ with respect to }x,\]

i.e. \(\frac{\mathrm{d}^{2}y}{\mathrm{d}x^{2}}\) is the gradient function for \(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\). Hence we have the following results:

\begin{tabular}{|l|l|} \hline \(O\) & Concave downwards & Concave upwards \\ \hline As \(x\) increases, the gradient of the curve & As \(x\) increases, the gradient of the curve \\ decreases, i.e. f'(\(x\)) is decreasing. & increases, i.e. f'(\(x\)) is increasing. \\ f'(\(x\)) is decreasing \(\iff\) f"(\(x\)) \(<0\). & f'(\(x\)) is increasing \(\iff\) f"(\(x\)) \(>0\). \\ \hline \end{tabular}

Therefore, if f"(\(x\)) \(<0\) (resp. f"(\(x\)) \(>0\)) for all \(x\) in an interval \(I\), then curve of \(y=\mathrm{f}(x)\)**concave downwards** (resp. **concave upwards**) on \(I\).

#### Example 2.4.1

Determine the concavity of \(y=\mathrm{f}(x)=x^{3}-3x^{2}+1\) for (a) \(x>1\), (b) \(x<1\).

_Solution:_

\[\mathrm{f}(x)=x^{3}-3x^{2}+1\ \Rightarrow\ \ \mathrm{f}^{\ \ \ }(x)=3x^{2}-6x\text{ and }\ \ \ \mathrm{f}^{\ \ \ }(x)=6x-6.\]

(a) \(x>1\): f"(\(x\)) = \(6x-6>0\). curve is concave upwards on (1, \(\infty\)).

(b) \(x<1\): f"(\(x\)) = \(6x-6<0\). curve is concave downwards on (-\(\infty\), 1).

